                <note rend="inline" type="source">816.01/11: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in Guatemala</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Whitehouse</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-12-08T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 8, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>35. For your information and discreet use.</p>
                <p>The Department is giving the most careful consideration to all aspects of the
                    situation in connection with the recent revolution in Salvador, but is not yet
                    in a position to determine its course of action in relation to the present
                    regime until the receipt of further reports which it is now awaiting from
                    Salvador.</p>
                <p>As soon as the Department has reached a decision it will instruct you to
                    communicate with the government of the country to which you are accredited,
                    since the Department desires to act in harmony in this <pb facs="0313" n="193"
                        xml:id="pg_193"/> matter with the signatories of the Treaty of Peace and
                    Amity of 1923.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Managua [as No.] 214 and San José [as No.] 41.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
